<p class="lead">With the Model Code of Conduct in force for the Tamil Nadu Legislative Assembly election, cash seizures amounting to Rs 51,85,920 have emerged as the largest component of the total Rs 1,09,07,713.04 seized in Coimbatore district as of Wednesday, March 18, 2026, 6 a.m., during election surveillance, according to the Daily Seizure Report issued by the district administration. Flying squad teams, static surveillance teams and the police have been carrying out checks across the district to curb the use of money and gifts to influence voters.</p>

<p>The report indicates that all seizures were effected by flying squad teams (FST), static surveillance teams (SST) and the police. No seizures were reported by the Income Tax Department or the State Prohibition and Excise Department in the same period for this tally, officials said. Separate action on tax evasion or liquor smuggling may still be taken by those agencies outside this specific election-surveillance count. The figures are updated daily and shared with the Election Commission and higher authorities as part of standard monitoring during polls.</p>

<p>Coimbatore district, with 10 Assembly constituencies and over 27 lakh registered voters, is among the high-stakes regions in western Tamil Nadu. The deployment of surveillance teams has been stepped up since the Model Code came into effect, with particular attention to movement of cash, liquor and valuables that could be linked to electoral inducement. Check posts, random inspections and intelligence-based operations have all contributed to the seizure figures.</p>

<p>Across Tamil Nadu, districts have reported varying seizure volumes depending on population, terrain and intensity of campaigning. Coimbatore's figures reflect both urban density and the volume of road and commercial activity. Officials said teams had been instructed to remain alert without creating undue panic among the public. Training sessions for squad members have emphasised courtesy and clarity when explaining why a search or document check is being conducted.</p>

<p>The Election Commission's emphasis on free and fair polls has translated into visible presence of enforcement machinery on the ground. In several neighbourhoods, residents said they had noticed more frequent police patrols and temporary checkpoints compared with non-election months. While some commuters reported minor delays during peak hours, most acknowledged that the checks were part of the electoral process.</p>

<h2>What the numbers show</h2>

<p>The total value of cash and valuables seized crossed Rs 1.09 crore in the period under review. Cash alone accounted for Rs 51.85 lakh, underscoring the focus of enforcement on unaccounted currency. The remainder comprised other valuables and items that were confiscated when teams found them to be in suspicious circumstances or without adequate documentation during inspections.</p>

<p>Officials said a large number of individual seizures had been recorded, with teams handing over seized material to returning officers and maintaining proper records. In one instance reported from the Thondamuthur Assembly constituency, a flying squad team handed over part of seized cash to the Returning Officer, following the procedure laid down by the Election Commission. Similar processes have been followed in other constituencies. Each seizure is logged with time, place, amount or description of goods, and the identity of the person from whom material was taken, subject to verification.</p>

<p>Aggregation of figures at district level allows the administration to compare trends across constituencies and to redeploy teams if certain areas show unusual spikes in suspicious movement. The Rs 1.09 crore headline figure is a cumulative total; individual seizures range from smaller amounts carried without papers to larger bundles that trigger deeper inquiry. Jewellery, mobile phones and other valuables sometimes form part of the non-cash component when they are suspected to be meant for distribution or are unaccompanied by valid bills.</p>

<p>The district administration has urged the public not to carry cash exceeding Rs 50,000 or goods valued above Rs 10,000 in bulk without valid supporting documents, to avoid unnecessary questioning and delays at checkpoints. Legitimate business transactions and personal travel with proper proof are not barred, but officials have asked citizens to keep bills, invoices or bank withdrawal slips handy when carrying large sums.</p>

<h2>Surveillance on the ground</h2>

<p>Flying squad teams move swiftly based on complaints and tip-offs, while static surveillance teams maintain vigil at sensitive locations. The police complement these teams with highway checks and searches in urban pockets. Coimbatore city and its suburban areas, along with major roads leading to Kerala and other districts, have seen regular vehicle checks.</p>

<p>Election officials said the objective was not to harass ordinary citizens but to ensure a level playing field and to deter distribution of cash or freebies in violation of the Model Code. Teams have been briefed on the distinction between genuine cases and those requiring further investigation. In border areas and commercial hubs, intensity of checking has been higher during peak hours. Bus stands, marriage halls and places where public gatherings are common have also been on the radar, given past instances elsewhere in the State of cash being distributed under the guise of social functions.</p>

<p>Coordination between revenue, police and election machinery has been tighter than in routine law-and-order situations. Daily briefings at the district level review seizure data, complaints received and any incidents of tension at checkpoints. Quick response teams stand by to defuse disputes if a motorist or party worker objects to a prolonged inspection.</p>

<p>Video surveillance teams have also been deployed across the 10 Assembly segments to monitor sensitive pockets. The district has 3,540 polling stations, and preparedness includes ensuring that inducement does not influence voter choice in the final days before polling. The Collector and senior police officers have held review meetings with team leaders to fine-tune deployment based on ground feedback.</p>

<h2>Model Code and voter confidence</h2>

<p>The Model Code of Conduct is a set of guidelines issued by the Election Commission that regulate the conduct of political parties and candidates during elections. It restricts misuse of official machinery, largesse and appeals to caste or communal feelings, among other things. Surveillance on cash and valuables is part of enforcing provisions against bribery and undue influence.</p>

<p>In Coimbatore, as in other districts, political parties have been reminded to account for election expenditure and to avoid cash distribution. The seizure figures are often cited in media and debates as an indicator of how strictly the code is being enforced. Officials cautioned against reading every seizure as proof of electoral malpractice—some cases may involve procedural issues or lack of documentation rather than proven intent to bribe voters.</p>

<p>Civil society groups and election watchdogs have welcomed the visible enforcement but have also asked for transparency in how seized amounts are eventually dealt with after due process. The Election Commission has laid down procedures for depositing seized cash in treasury or bank and for release if legitimate claims are established. Observers appointed by the Commission monitor whether enforcement is even-handed across parties and regions.</p>

<p>Legal experts note that seizure alone does not establish an electoral offence; prosecution depends on evidence of intent to influence voters. Many cases end in release of amounts after documentation is verified. The high visibility of cash figures nonetheless serves as a deterrent to casual violation of spending norms and reinforces the message that the poll process is under watch.</p>

<h2>District context</h2>

<p>Coimbatore's industrial and commercial profile means large cash movement is not unusual in normal times. Jewellery, textile and trade businesses often handle significant transactions. During the election period, the same patterns attract closer scrutiny. Traders' associations have requested sensitivity from teams so that genuine business is not disrupted, while supporting action against any misuse of money for electoral gain.</p>

<p>The district shares borders with Kerala and other Tamil Nadu districts; inter-state movement of vehicles is monitored to prevent smuggling of liquor or cash for distribution. Excise and police teams coordinate on liquor-related offences, though the Daily Seizure Report referred to here focuses on FST, SST and police seizures of cash and valuables under the election surveillance framework.</p>

<p>First-time voters and young electors have been targeted through awareness campaigns alongside enforcement. The Collector has called for full participation and ethical voting, reinforcing that inducements undermine the democratic process. Colleges and youth organisations have been roped in to spread the message that votes should be cast freely, without fear or favour.</p>

<p>Women voters and senior citizens, who form a significant share of the electorate in several urban wards, have been assured that polling stations will be accessible and that assistance will be available where needed. The linkage between surveillance on inducements and voter trust is often stressed in district communications—that when money cannot buy votes, the value of each ballot increases.</p>

<h2>Political parties and complaints</h2>

<p>Political parties have traded charges over enforcement, with some alleging that flying squads target their workers disproportionately and others welcoming strict action. The district election machinery has maintained that operations are guided by the Commission's instructions and are not directed at any single party. Representations received from parties are forwarded to observers and the Commission for clarification.</p>

<p>Party agents and candidates have been told to keep meticulous accounts of election expenditure and to avoid cash transactions that cannot be explained. Violations can attract not only seizure but also penalties under election law. The cumulative seizure figure in Coimbatore is one data point in a statewide picture that the Commission reviews ahead of polling.</p>

<h2>What happens next</h2>

<p>Seizure figures are expected to rise as polling day approaches, when surveillance typically peaks. Teams will continue random checks, and complaints through the cVIGIL app and helplines will be acted upon. Political parties may move the Election Commission if they perceive selective enforcement; the Commission has mechanisms to address such representations.</p>

<p>Individuals from whom cash or goods are seized can present valid documents to establish the legitimacy of their holdings. The Collector has stated in media briefings that seized cash may be returned if valid proof is produced, subject to verification. This is intended to balance enforcement with fairness to genuine cases.</p>

<p>Voters in Coimbatore can expect continued visibility of flying squads and police teams until the conclusion of the election process. Officials have asked for public cooperation and timely reporting of any attempt to buy votes or distribute gifts in violation of the law. The district administration has also reiterated that intimidation or bribery should be reported immediately through official channels so that teams can respond without delay.</p>

<p>As polling day nears, the tempo of checks may increase further, especially on routes used for last-minute campaigning. Residents travelling for work across constituencies are advised to plan for possible short delays at nakas and to carry identity and transaction papers if they move with large sums for legitimate reasons.</p>

<h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

<h3>Why was my vehicle checked?</h3>
<p>During the Model Code of Conduct, teams check vehicles for unaccounted cash, liquor and valuables that could be used to influence voters. Carrying large cash without supporting documents may lead to temporary seizure pending verification.</p>

<h3>How much cash can I carry legally?</h3>
<p>There is no blanket ban on carrying cash, but officials have advised against carrying more than Rs 50,000 without valid documents such as bank withdrawal slips or business invoices. Bulk goods above Rs 10,000 in value should be supported by bills where applicable.</p>

<h3>Who can I contact if I face harassment?</h3>
<p>Complaints can be lodged with the district control room, the Election Commission helpline, or through the cVIGIL mobile app. Senior election officials and the Collector's office also take up grievances related to overreach or misconduct by teams.</p>

<h3>Will seized cash be returned?</h3>
<p>If you establish the legitimacy of the cash or goods with proper documentation, authorities have said seized amounts may be returned after verification. Procedures vary by case; contact the office of the Returning Officer or the district administration for specifics.</p>

<h3>Where do the seizure figures come from?</h3>
<p>They are compiled from the Daily Seizure Report issued by the district administration, aggregating seizures by flying squads, static surveillance teams and the police. Figures are as of the stated date and time and are updated periodically. The report is part of the Election Commission's monitoring framework and is used for statewide and national reporting on enforcement during the poll period.</p>
